metadata.name: BWEEPS  #45
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #47
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #222
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #114
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #136
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: OnÃ¥bar #20
metadata.description:
We are filling our one and only world with our endless cities, roads and structures, for as far as the eye can see. We are covering nature, our home entrusted to us, with our growing waste and trash. We are burying what was once green and blue, under yellow and gray. We are replacing what is pure and beautiful with soulless illusions slipped into our hands in exchange for what makes us human...

Yet we still keep trying to reach what we've been intentionally and continuously driving away from us. What we fool ourselves as to be touchable any time we want, is getting more and more unreachable in reality. And as long as we continue to do the same things, we will never be able to reach it.

* * *

OnÃ¥bar, Unreachable in Swedish, started to come to life during one of the hardest periods of my life, the hardships of which mostly caused by my own self. With every line of its code, with every brush of its color, it helped me take one step further to leave that hardship behind.

I painted OnÃ¥bar using only rectangles, with a long-evolved version of an algorithm I first experimented in my TIÂ·ME series. The mostly colorful nature of OnÃ¥bar's palettes come from my replenished hope for reaching the unreachable.

The more I worked on OnÃ¥bar, the more it helped me realize that what seems to be unreachable, in any aspect of life, only seems so because we do everything to keep it stay unreachable, instead of taking the necessary steps towards reaching it. And now, this feels just like the best time to take that first step...

* * *

I hope you will like OnÃ¥bar as much as I liked working on it. Thank you very much for collecting and for your continuous support.

10% of primary and secondary sales will go to fxhash team; thank you for what you are doing.

Self reserved pieces are for promised gifts to my collectors.

Press S to save as PNG. To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL (e.g. "&s=1600"), press Enter and then press S.

metadata.name: Cry Diversity #90
metadata.description:
Cry Diversity is just that - a cry for greater diversity and equality in the genArt community. The UNESCO Universal Declaration on Cultural Diversity beautifully states, âAs a source of exchange, innovation and creativity, cultural diversity is as necessary for humankind as biodiversity is for nature.âÂ  Who better to usher in an age of true appreciation for, and active promotion of cultural diversity than a community of artists and collectors.

Excerpts from the UNESCO declaration are embedded in the piece in the form of asemic writing, infusing the piece with the power of the message as it charms the eye.Â  The collector will also be able to select one of twenty affirmations to be embedded in the work.Â  Each minted edition will stand as a prayer flag waving permanently on the blockchain spreading its message of belief in a world where we are all valued and respected.Â  Cry Diversity will be free to collect, but it comes with a challenge.Â  The collector is expected to actively research the cryptoArt community to find an artist new to them that is a member of an underrepresented group (female, LBGTQIA2+, female identifying, non-binary, POC, global south, etc.).Â  They are then expected to actively promote that artist and their work for at least one week.Â  They are expected to personally raise their voice.Â  Cry Diversity is the second in a series of projects (see the companion piece fx(elevate)) designed to bring attention to individual artists as well as to the value of true commitment to diversity within our community.Â  It will not be the last.

It is time to make our cries heard and our actions felt!


Collection Mechanics:
In the initial week after launch, holders of any of my past fx(hash) projects may mint a free edition.  Beginning in the 2nd week, the project will be open to the public for an additional week. Un-minted editions will be burned at the expiration of the 2nd week.

Minting Instructions: 
1) Use the Randomized Params button to explore outputs.  
2) When a design emerges that you want to mint, lock the Seed Input param.  
3) Choose your Cry.  Lock it.
4) Mint & enjoy. 

Parameter Descriptions: 
a) Seed Input: Each output is a unique result based on your wallet address and the seed value. If you have recorded the seed for a given output as you explore, you can simply type in the seed to retrieve it.
b) Cry: What do you want our community to symbolize?  Respect, diversity, compassion?  Choose your favorite characteristic.  It will be baked into your output.

Project Details:
This work uses the spectral.js library for the development of color palettes. 

Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in June, 2023, this work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

The minter shares secondary royalties with the creator and a beneficiary.

Dimensionless design responds to window size.

Interactions:
Press [D] in live mode to download. Press [S] in live mode to download a high resolution output suitable for printing.
